solr_doc_hash.collection_name: The Earl Conrad/Harriet Tubman Research Materials
title: Research Correspondence
title_sort: Research Correspondence
note: This series contains letters from Earl Conrad to potential sources of information relating to the life and activities of Harriet Tubman, and their responses. The potential sources included historians specializing in the abolitionist movement and the post-Civil War years, librarians in the various communities in which Harriet Tubman lived or based her operations, and such national repositories as the Library of Congress, National Archives, and the British Museum where the official records documenting her life and activities were kept.

solr_doc_hash.collection_name: The Earl Conrad/Harriet Tubman Research Materials
title: Research Notes
title_sort: Research Notes
note: Earl Conrad's notes taken from relevant published works. These works include histories of the period in which Harriet Tubman was active, biographies of contemporary figures, articles in various newspapers and magazines, (especially those which focused their attention on social movements, i.e. Abolition and Women's Suffrage) such as the National Anti-Slavery Standard, Liberator, and Boston Commonwealth. Notes were also taken from the general press (New York Times and New York Herald), the black press (Frederick Douglass' Newspaper), and local newspapers (Auburn Citizen, Post-Standard).

solr_doc_hash.collection_name: The Earl Conrad/Harriet Tubman Research Materials
title: Publishers' Correspondence
title_sort: Publishers' Correspondence
note: Includes Conrad's correspondence with various publishers in an attempt to get his completed manuscripts on Tubman published. The letters are important in that they illustrate the strong resistance put forth by the publishing industry against anything relating to the Black Experience, even where it dealt with an historical figure of Harriet Tubman's stature. These letters also document the results of an attempt to have the work published in serial form in magazines and newspapers.
